### Remarks

*   Spinless particles like pions are unstable and interact strongly. The interaction term in the [Hamiltonian](/Hamiltonian_(quantum_mechanics)) is not simple.
*   The [Sine–Gordon equation](/Sine%E2%80%93Gordon_equation) is a notable example of an [Integrable system](/Integrable_system).
*   To merge quantum mechanics and [special relativity](/Special_relativity), you need a multi-particle theory – [quantum field theory](/Quantum_field_theory). The Klein–Gordon equation reappears as the equation for components of all free quantum fields.

[Steven Weinberg](/Steven_Weinberg) famously omitted relativistic wave mechanics from his quantum mechanics lectures, calling its usual presentation "profoundly misleading." Others, like [Walter Greiner](/Walter_Greiner), prefer the long, historical route, finding it pedagogically necessary. The free solutions of these original equations still matter in quantum field theory; they form the basis of the [Fock space](/Fock_space) and allow us to express quantum fields.

